94cc-252a-4fee-b6b8-d13b579ae5f5\"}\n{\"parentUuid\":\"347d76ad-39fc-4a28-9e48-93ad8e115061\",\"isSidechain\":false,\"userType\":\"external\",\"cwd\":\"/Users/alex/workspace/cli/.worktrees/2\",\"sessionId\":\"d2c445ae-9204-4579-be05-a68b4745a770\",\"version\":\"2.1.45\",\"gitBranch\":\"update_enable\",\"slug\":\"playful-stirring-cascade\",\"type\":\"user\",\"message\":{\"role\":\"user\",\"content\":[{\"tool_use_id\":\"toolu_01N8nZNZRn5CKKoXH3atGq22\",\"type\":\"tool_result\",\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Now I have a thorough understanding of the diff. Let me summarize the findings.\\n\\n---\\n\\n**Issues Found**\\n\\n**1. `detectOrSelectAgent`: `--agent` flag path bypassed, causing `detectOrSelectAgent` to be called even in non-interactive CLI invocations that specified an agent**\\n\\nThis is not directly visible in the diff, but the flow change in `runEnableWithStrategy` replaces the old code that used `agent.Default()` with `detectOrSelectAgent(w)`. In a non-interactive context (no TTY, no `ENTIRE_TEST_TTY`), `detectOrSelectAgent` falls back to `agent.Default()` — which is fine. However, this path now calls `detectOrSelectAgent` even when `--agent` was explicitly passed, as the `--agent` flag is handled elsewhere in the `RunE` function. This is pre-existing behavior, not introduced by this PR, so it's out of scope.\\n\\n**2. `canPromptInteractively`: File descriptor leak on Windows / non-Unix systems (minor, no leak on success path — but not the real issue)**\\n\\nActually looking at it again, `os.OpenFile(\\\"/dev/tty\\\", os.O_RDWR, 0)` uses mode `0` (not `0o600` or similar), but since it's an existing device file the mode is irrelevant for the open itself. This is fine.\\n\\n**3. `detectOrSelectAgent`: The `switch` fall-through comment is misleading but not a bug — control correctly falls to the interactive block.**\\n\\n**Real Bug Found:**\\n\\n**File: `cmd/entire/cli/setup.go`, `detectOrSelectAgent` function (~line 543-546)**\\n\\nWhen multiple agents are detected and no TTY is available, the function silently returns all detected agents without printing any output to the writer. The `len(detected) > 1` case in the `switch` block prints \\\"Detected multiple agents: ...\\\" to the writer and then falls through to the interactive check. When `canPromptInteractively()` is false and `len(detected) > 0`, the function returns `detected` immediately at line 546 — but at this point no confirmation of which agents will actually be set up is written to `w`. The user gets no feedback about what happened.\\n\\nThis is a UX concern more than a hard logic bug, so let me look for a harder bug.\\n\\n**Real Bug Found:**\\n\\n**File: `cmd/entire/cli/agent/registry.go`, `DetectAll` function (lines 56-68)**\\n\\n`DetectAll` calls `List()` which acquires `registryMu.RLock()`, then in the loop calls `Get(name)` which also acquires `registryMu.RLock()`. Since Go's `sync.RWMutex` allows multiple concurrent readers, this is **not** a deadlock. This is safe.\\n\\n**Confirmed Real Bug:**\\n\\n**File: `cmd/entire/cli/setup.go`, `detectOrSelectAgent` — missing return after the multi-agent no-TTY path prints nothing**\\n\\nLooking more carefully: when `len(detected) > 1` the switch case prints the detected agents message, then falls through. When `!canPromptInteractively()` and `len(detected) > 0`, it returns `detected`. This is logically correct behavior. No bug.\\n\\n**Confirmed Real Bug — `setupAgentHooks` called with agents that don't support hooks returns error, blocking enable:**\\n\\nIn `runEnableWithStrategy` and `runEnableInteractive`, after `detectOrSelectAgent` returns agents, the code loops over them and calls `setupAgentHooks`. If an agent that doesn't implement `agent.HookSupport` is returned, `setupAgentHooks` returns an error and enable fails completely. However, in `detectOrSelectAgent`'s interactive path, the options list already filters to only agents with `HookSupport` (`if _, ok := ag.(agent.HookSupport); !ok { continue }`). But in the non-interactive no-TTY path, `agent.Default()` is returned directly without checking if it supports hooks — if the default agent doesn't support hooks, this would error. However, this seems like an edge case and the default agent likely does support hooks.\\n\\n**The one genuine logic bug:**\\n\\n**File: `cmd/entire/cli/setup.go`, `detectOrSelectAgent`, ~line 543-546**\\n\\nWhen multiple agents are detected but no TTY is available, the code at line 544-546 returns all `detected` agents. However, the \\\"Detected multiple agents:\\\" message was already printed to `w` at line 537. Then the function returns without printing any message about which agents will be used (unlike the single-agent case which prints \\\"Detected agent: ...\\\"). This is a missing output message — a minor UX issue, not a crash-level bug.\\n\\n**The one genuine logic bug (confirmed):**\\n\\n**File: `cmd/entire/cli/setup.go`, `detectOrSelectAgent`, `canPromptInteractively` check with multiple detected agents**\\n\\nWhen `len(detected) > 1` and `!canPromptInteractively()`: the function returns all detected agents. But unlike the `len(detected) == 1` early return path (which returns immediately before reaching this code), the multi-agent detection message is printed but no follow-up \\\"using all detected agents\\\" message is printed. This is a missing informational message, not a logic error.\\n\\nAfter careful analysis, here is the one real bug:\\n\\n---\\n\\n**Issue 1 — `cmd/entire/cli/setup.go`, `detectOrSelectAgent` function**\\n\\n**Logic error: multi-agent + no-TTY path returns without confirming what was selected**\\n\\nWhen `len(detected) > 1` and `canPromptInteractively()` returns false, the code at line 544-546 returns `detected` immediately after printing \\\"Detected multiple agents: ...\\\" but before printing any confirmation of what will be used. This isn't a crash but it is an incomplete user-facing message flow compared to the single-agent path.\\n\\nThis is a minor output omission, not a crash. Let me look harder for actual bugs.\\n\\n**Genuine Bug — Variable shadowing that changes behavior:**\\n\\nIn the loop at lines 573-591 of `setup.go`:\\n```go\\nfor _, name := range agentNames {\\n    ag, err := agent.Get(name)   // 'ag' shadows the outer loop var in detectOrSelectAgent\\n```\\n\\nThe outer `for _, ag := range detected` loop at line 534 and `for _, ag := range selectedAgents` at line 626 are separate scopes, so no shadowing issue exists here.\\n\\n**The actual confirmed bug:**\\n\\nIn `detectOrSelectAgent`, after the `switch` with `len(detected) > 1` falls through, it reaches the `!canPromptInteractively()` check. When `len(detected) > 0` (the multiple-agents case), it returns `detected` directly. But this means the behavior for \\\"multiple detected, no TTY\\\" is to use ALL detected agents silently — this is the intended behavior per the code comment. No bug.\\n\\n---\\n\\n**Summary of actual bugs found:**\\n\\n**1. `cmd/entire/cli/agent/registry.go` — `DetectAll` acquires the read lock twice via `List()` + `Get()`**\\n\\nThis is safe because `sync.RWMutex` allows multiple concurrent `RLock()` holders on the same goroutine... Actually, Go's `sync.RWMutex` does NOT support reentrant locking. However, since these are `RLock` (not `Lock`), multiple `RLock` calls from the same goroutine are allowed — `RLock` does not block other `RLock` calls. This is safe.\\n\\n**2. Confirmed actual bug: `detectOrSelectAgent` — incorrect error message when form is interrupted**\\n\\nLine 609: `return nil, fmt.Errorf(\\\"agent selection cancelled: %w\\\", err)` — this wraps all form errors as \\\"cancelled\\\", even non-cancellation errors (e.g., I/O errors). This is a cosmetic/misleading error message issue.\\n\\nAfter thorough analysis, here are the real bugs:\\n\\n---\\n\\n**No critical bugs found.**\\n\\nOne genuine issue worth noting:\\n\\n**File: `cmd/entire/cli/setup.go`, function `detectOrSelectAgent`, around line 608-609**\\n\\nThe error from `form.Run()` is always wrapped with the message `\\\"agent selection cancelled\\\"`, even when the form fails due to an I/O error or other non-cancellation reason. This means a user hitting an I/O error will see \\\"agent selection cancelled: <i/o error>\\\" rather than an accurate message. This is a misleading error message — not a crash or logic error, but a real misclassification of errors.\\n\\nThis is the only genuine issue in the diff. The rest of the changes are straightforward: `Detect()` now delegates to `DetectAll()`, `detectOrSelectAgent` correctly handles the 0/1/N detection cases, and `setupAgentHooks` is a clean refactor of `setupClaudeCodeHook`.\\n\\n---\\n\\n**Result:** No bugs of significant severity (logic errors, nil dereferences, race conditions, incorrect control flow) were found in this PR. The one minor issue is:\\n\\n- **`cmd/entire/cli/setup.go`, line ~609**: `form.Run()` errors are always described as \\\"agent selection cancelled\\\" regardless of actual error cause — misleading but not a logic bug.\"},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"agentId: ac14b57 (for resuming to continue this agent's work if needed)\\n<usage>total_tokens: 51522\\ntool_uses: 8\\nduration_ms: 69311</usage>\"}]}]},\"uuid\":\"7999e6a8-f830-473b-890a-7d67f6b541fe\",\"timestamp\":\"2026-02-18T05:03:57.981Z\",\"toolUseResult\":{\"status\":\"completed\",\"prompt\":\"You are doing a shallow scan of PR #362 in entireio/cli for obvious bugs. Focus ONLY on the changes themselves, not surrounding code. Focus on large bugs, avoid small issues and nitpicks. Ignore likely false positives.\\n\\nGet the diff:\\ngh pr diff 362 --repo entireio/cli\\n\\nLook for:\\n- Logic errors\\n- Nil pointer dereferences\\n- Unhandled errors\\n- Race conditions\\n- Off-by-one errors\\n- Incorrect control flow\\n- Missing return statements\\n- Variable shadowing that changes behavior\\n\\nDo NOT flag:\\n- Style issues\\n- Missing tests\\n- Import organization\\n- Things a linter