ents don't require a config directory.\\\")\\nfmt.Fprintln(w)\\n```\\n\\nThese are user-facing messages printed through `w` (an `io.Writer` passed from Cobra command context), which is the correct pattern. No violation here.\\n\\n---\\n\\n**Issue 5: `detectOrSelectAgent` wraps form cancellation errors with a generic message that swallows the specific error context from the user perspective**\\n\\nFile: `/Users/alex/workspace/cli/.worktrees/2/cmd/entire/cli/setup.go`, line 609\\n\\n```go\\nif err := form.Run(); err != nil {\\n    return nil, fmt.Errorf(\\\"agent selection cancelled: %w\\\", err)\\n}\\n```\\n\\nWhen `form.Run()` returns `huh.ErrUserAborted` (the user pressed Escape/Ctrl-C), this error is wrapped and propagated up to `runEnableWithStrategy` / `runEnableInteractive`, which further wraps it as `\\\"agent selection failed: %w\\\"`. The resulting error message printed to stderr by `main.go` would be something like: `agent selection failed: agent selection cancelled: EOF`. This is not user-friendly. Per CLAUDE.md's error handling pattern, when a custom user-friendly message is already appropriate, a `SilentError` should be returned after printing the message directly to stderr. The callers do not use `SilentError` here.\\n\\n**Relevant CLAUDE.md quote:**\\n> \\\"Use `NewSilentError()` when you want to print a custom, user-friendly error message instead of the raw error\\\"\\n> \\\"Commands return `NewSilentError(err)` when they've already printed a custom message\\\"\\n\\nHowever, `detectOrSelectAgent` is not a command — it's a helper called from within command `RunE` functions. The responsibility to handle the error gracefully lies with `runEnableWithStrategy`/`runEnableInteractive`. Those functions return the error directly without printing a user-friendly message and without using `SilentError`, meaning `main.go` will print the raw wrapped error. This is a legitimate concern.\\n\\n**Severity: Medium** - The SilentError pattern is not applied to the user-abort flow.\\n\\n---\\n\\n**Issue 6: `detectOrSelectAgent` in `setup.go` — The `\\\"no agents selected\\\"` error is not handled gracefully with `SilentError`**\\n\\nFile: `/Users/alex/workspace/cli/.worktrees/2/cmd/entire/cli/setup.go`, line 613\\n\\n```go\\nif len(selectedAgentNames) == 0 {\\n    return nil, errors.New(\\\"no agents selected\\\")\\n}\\n```\\n\\nSame issue as above — this error propagates through `runEnableWithStrategy`/`runEnableInteractive` to `main.go` which will print the raw error message. For a user-facing flow that prompts interactively, \\\"no agents selected\\\" printed raw is awkward. A `SilentError` after printing a friendly message would be more appropriate.\\n\\n**Relevant CLAUDE.md quote:**\\n> \\\"Use `NewSilentError()` when you want to print a custom, user-friendly error message instead of the raw error\\\"\\n\\n**Severity: Medium** - Same as Issue 5, SilentError pattern not applied.\\n\\n---\\n\\n### Summary Table\\n\\n| # | File | Approx. Line | Issue | Severity | CLAUDE.md Rule |\\n|---|------|-------------|-------|----------|----------------|\\n| 1 | `agent/registry.go` | 55-68 | `DetectAll()` acquires/releases lock per iteration (not atomic like old impl) | Low | Code quality |\\n| 2 | `setup.go` | 637-638 | `os.Getenv` called twice for same key in `canPromptInteractively` | Low | \\\"Follow standard Go idioms\\\" |\\n| 5 | `setup.go` | 609 | User-abort of agent selection form not handled with `SilentError`; raw error reaches `main.go` | Medium | \\\"Use `NewSilentError()` when you want to print a custom, user-friendly error message\\\" |\\n| 6 | `setup.go` | 613 | \\\"no agents selected\\\" error not handled with `SilentError` | Medium | \\\"Use `NewSilentError()` when you want to print a custom, user-friendly error message\\\" |\\n\\n---\\n\\n### Non-Issues Confirmed\\n\\n- **Accessibility**: `detectOrSelectAgent` correctly uses `NewAccessibleForm()` (not `huh.NewForm()`) for the multi-select prompt. Compliant.\\n- **Test par