/2\",\"sessionId\":\"d2c445ae-9204-4579-be05-a68b4745a770\",\"version\":\"2.1.45\",\"gitBranch\":\"update_enable\",\"slug\":\"playful-stirring-cascade\",\"type\":\"user\",\"message\":{\"role\":\"user\",\"content\":[{\"tool_use_id\":\"toolu_015XHeoivKHUU9xXL2S1gvkr\",\"type\":\"tool_result\",\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Now I have a thorough understanding of the PR. Let me summarize my findings:\\n\\n---\\n\\n## PR #362 Review: Issues Found\\n\\n### Issue 1 - Breaking Change: `detectOrSelectAgent` return type changed from single agent to slice, but the call sites in `runEnableWithStrategy` and `runEnableInteractive` now loop over agents without saving agent state per-agent to settings\\n\\n**File:** `cmd/entire/cli/setup.go`\\n**Historical context:** Commit `b7fd14bd` (the immediately prior commit on this branch, \\\"update entire enable experience\\\") introduced `detectOrSelectAgent` returning a single `agent.Agent`. This PR changes it to return `[]agent.Agent`. The PR is a direct extension of that work.\\n\\nThe problem: `runEnableWithStrategy` and `runEnableInteractive` both now do:\\n\\n```go\\nagents, err := detectOrSelectAgent(w)\\n// ...\\nfor _, ag := range agents {\\n    if _, err := setupAgentHooks(ag, localDev, forceHooks); err != nil {\\n        return fmt.Errorf(\\\"failed to setup %s hooks: %w\\\", ag.Type(), err)\\n    }\\n}\\n```\\n\\nThey install hooks for multiple agents, but then continue to call `runEnableWithStrategy`/`runEnableInteractive` which eventually write settings (`.entire/settings.json`) — those downstream calls only record one agent (or possibly none). The settings struct records a single strategy, not a list of agents. If two agents are selected, hooks for both get installed, but the settings file isn't updated to record both. This could cause `isFullyEnabled()` to check `GetAgentsWithHooksInstalled()` correctly (since that checks actual hook files), but any code that reads settings to know which agents are configured would only see one.\\n\\nMore concretely: when `detectOrSelectAgent` returns two agents and the loop installs both, the subsequent settings-writing code (further down in `runEnableWithStrategy`) was written to handle a single agent. No settings field was added to track multiple agents. This is a silent partial state issue.\\n\\n### Issue 2 - The multi-agent detection + no-TTY path is inconsistent with the single-agent detection path\\n\\n**File:** `cmd/entire/cli/setup.go`, function `detectOrSelectAgent`\\n\\n```go\\ncase len(detected) > 1:\\n    // Multiple agents detected — prompt the user to confirm which to enable\\n    agentTypes := make([]string, 0, len(detected))\\n    ...\\n    fmt.Fprintf(w, \\\"Detected multiple agents: %s\\\\n\\\", strings.Join(agentTypes, \\\", \\\"))\\n    fmt.Fprintln(w)\\n    // Fall through to the interactive multi-select below\\n```\\n\\nThen immediately after the switch:\\n\\n```go\\nif !canPromptInteractively() {\\n    if len(detected) > 0 {\\n        // Multiple agents detected but no TTY — use all of them\\n        return detected, nil\\n    }\\n    ...\\n}\\n```\\n\\nWhen multiple agents are detected and there is no TTY, the function prints \\\"Detected multiple agents: ...\\\" but then silently returns all of them without any confirmation. This is inconsistent with the single-agent path, which prints \\\"Detected agent: X\\\" and returns immediately at the top of the switch. The no-TTY multi-agent path prints the \\\"Detected multiple agents\\\" banner, then falls into the `canPromptInteractively()` check — the message before the switch implies an interactive prompt is coming, but none happens. This could confuse users in non-interactive environments (CI) who see \\\"Detected multiple agents\\\" but get no indication that all were selected automatically.\\n\\n### Issue 3 - `DetectAll()` in `agent/registry.go` calls `Get()` while holding no lock, but the old `Detect()` iterated directly over the locked `registry`\\n\\n**File:** `cmd/entire/cli/agent/registry.go`\\n\\nThe old `Detect()` held `registryMu.RLock()` for its entire loop. The new `DetectAll()` calls `List()` (which acquires and releases the lock), then calls `Get()` for each name (which acquires and releases the lock per call). This is correct and safe — the \\\"safer locking\\\" commit `505ad951` established this pattern for `AllProtectedDirs()` specifically to avoid calling agent methods while holding the lock (since `DetectPresence()` does filesystem I/O). The new `DetectAll()` correctly follows this pattern. This is not a bug.\\n\\nHowever, there is a subtle issue: `DetectAll()` calls `Get(name)` which can return an error if the name isn't found, then silently `continue`s. Between `List()` releasing its lock and `Get(name)` acquiring it, an agent could theoretically be unregistered (unlikely in practice since `Register` is only called from `init()`). This is a theoretical race but not a practical problem given how registration works.\\n\\n### Issue 4 - `setupAgentHooks` nolint comment is stale/misleading\\n\\n**File:** `cmd/entire/cli/setup.go`, line 502:\\n\\n```go\\nfunc setupAgentHooks(ag agent.Agent, localDev, forceHooks bool) (int, error) { //nolint:unparam // return value used by setupAgentHooksNonInteractive\\n```\\n\\nThe comment says \\\"return value used by setupAgentHooksNonInteractive\\\" but `setupAgentHooksNonInteractive` does not call `setupAgentHooks` — it directly calls `hookAgent.InstallHooks()`. This comment was inherited from the prior commit `b7fd14bd` and is inaccurate. The actual callers in `runEnableWithStrategy` and `runEnableInteractive` loop over the return value in a `for range` and ignore the `int` count. The `//nolint:unparam` suppresses a lint warning about the unused return value, but the justification comment is wrong, which makes it harder to audit whether the suppression is legitimate.\\n\\n### Summary\\n\\nThe most substantive issue is **Issue 1**: the PR transitions `detectOrSelectAgent` from returning a single agent to a slice, and wires up hook installation for each agent, but the settings persistence downstream in `runEnableWithStrategy` and `runEnableInteractive` was written assuming a single agent. Multi-agent selection will install hooks for multiple agents but not fully persist that state. The second concern (**Issue 2**) is a UX inconsistency in the no-TTY multi-agent path.\"},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"agentId: a9bc1aa (for resuming to continue this agent's work if needed)\\n<usage>total_tokens: 63695\\ntool_uses: 17\\nduration_ms: 84548</usage>\"}]}]},\"uuid\":\"62e2330f-0ddc-43eb-8321-3f56462c9b86\",\"timestamp\":\"2026-02-18T05:04:17.932Z\",\"toolUseResult\":{\"status\":\"completed\",\"prompt\":\"You are reviewing PR #362 in entireio/cli by examining git blame and history for modified files.\\n\\nFirst, get the list of files changed:\\ngh pr diff 362 --repo entireio/cli --name-only\\n\\nThe main files are:\\n- cmd/entire/cli/agent/registry.go\\n- cmd/entire/cli/setup.go\\n- cmd/entire/cli/setup_test.go\\n- cmd/entire/cli/strategy/registry.go\\n\\nFor each modified file (except test files), run git log and git blame to understand the history:\\n- git log --oneline -20 -- <file>\\n- git blame <file> (for the areas around the modified code)\\n\\nLook for:\\n- Changes that might break existing behavior based on historical context\\n- Patterns that were intentionally established and are now being violated\\n- Code that was previously fixed for a specific reason and is being re-broken\\n\\nReturn any issues found with description, file, and historical context. If no issues, say so explicitly.\",\"agentId\":\"a9bc1aa\",\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Now I have a thorough understanding of the PR. Let me summarize my findings:\\n\\n---\\n\\n## PR #362 Review: Issues Found\\n\\n### Issue 1 - Breaking Change: `detectOrSelectAgent` return type changed from single agent to slice, but the call sites in `runEnableWithStrategy` and `runEna